source: Note: We treat categoriccal missing values by replacing it by mode and outliers with median and continous missing           values with mean.

# Plotting Categorical Variables in Dataset(Countplots and histograms are same)

A special case for the bar plot is when you want to show the number of observations in each category rather than computing a statistic for a second variable. This is similar to a histogram over a categorical, rather than quantitative, variable. In seaborn, itâ€™s easy to do so with the countplot() function:
Countplot() -  We use countplot to visualise the frequency of one variable
Show value counts for two categorical variables:

sns.countplot(y='education',hue='sex',data=dataset,palette='Set2')
plt.xlabel('Counts')
plt.title('Distribution of Education w.r.t sex')
plt.ylabel('Education')

Approach 2- The second approach adjusts the points along the categorical axis using an algorithm that prevents them from overlapping. It can give a better representation of the distribution of observations, although it only works well for relatively small datasets. This kind of plot is sometimes called a â€œbeeswarmâ€ and is drawn in seaborn by swarmplot(), which is activated by setting kind=â€swarmâ€ in catplot():
or we can also use swarmplot directly

tips = sns.load_dataset("tips") #loading in-built dataset

sns.catplot(x="day", y="total_bill", kind="swarm", data=tips)

STRIPLOT() USING TIPS DATASET



seaborn.stripplot(x=None, y=None, hue=None, data=None, order=None, hue_order=None, jitter=True, dodge=False, orient=None, color=None, palette=None, size=5, edgecolor='gray', linewidth=0, ax=None, **kwargs)


Use- Draw a scatterplot where one variable is categorical.
We add jitter to bring out the distribution of values:

#Nest the strips within a second categorical variable:

sns.stripplot(x='day',y='total_bill',data=tips,jitter=True,hue='day')

#Control strip order by passing an explicit order:

sns.stripplot(x="time", y="tip", data=tips)

BOX PLOT - The first is the familiar boxplot(). This kind of plot shows the three quartile values of the distribution along with extreme values. The â€œwhiskersâ€ extend to points that lie within 1.5 IQRs of the lower and upper quartile, and then observations that fall outside this range are displayed independently.
#Approach we can also use Boxplot using catplot
Violin Plots- A different approach is a violinplot(), which combines a boxplot with the kernel density estimation

Statistical Estimation With Catgories :

For other applications, rather than showing the distribution within each category, you might want to show an estimate of the central tendency of the values. Seaborn has two main ways to show this information
BARPLOT() - We use it to visualize the relationship between one categorical and numeric varibale.

Statistical analysis is a process of understanding how variables in a dataset relate to each other and how those relationships depend on other variables. Visualization can be a core component of this process because, when data are visualized properly, the human visual system can see trends and patterns that indicate a relationship.

Showing multiple relationships with facets

The best approach may be to make more than one plot. Because relplot() is based on the FacetGrid, this is easy to do. To show the influence of an additional variable, instead of assigning it to one of the semantic roles in the plot, use it to â€œfacetâ€ the visualization. This means that you make multiple axes and plot subsets of the data on each of them:
